description:
My favorite quote - ‚ÄúI want to be in uncomfortable situations because that‚Äôs when you learn and grow‚Äù.

That quote is related to personal growth, but it still applies to personal finance. A little bit.

When you‚Äôre not investing aggressively enough, you probably have too much money sitting in your bank account and you‚Äôre comfortable and you don‚Äôt need to question purchases.

But I want you to be a little bit uncomfortable. I want you to be investing so much of your money that you need to question whether you can afford that new pair of pants this month.

I want you to be investing so much that you can‚Äôt afford to order doordash and you force yourself to make a dinner out of random stuff in your pantry.

When you‚Äôre not investing enough and you‚Äôre too comfortable, you‚Äôre not going to challenge yourself on spending and you‚Äôre going to waste money.

I‚Äôm not telling you to cut out everything fun in your life. But if you‚Äôre a bit uncomfortable and you‚Äôve already spent money on going out for your friends birthday, then maybe you‚Äôll question your spending on some unnecessary expense instead of just buying it anyways. 

I know this sounds a little Dave Ramsey-ish and I know this isn‚Äôt for everyone. But this is what I did throughout a lot of my 20s and it worked well for me.

Remember to automate all of your investing.

And remember that you need to have an emergency fund and be saving for short term goals in a HYSA.

description:
Everyone always wants travel and have experiences in their 20s while they‚Äôre young. And I wanted those too.

But a dollar invested in your 20s is worth SO much more than a dollar invested in your 30s or 40s (when investing for 30-40 years).

So how do you balance this?

Cut back on things that don‚Äôt matter to you (in my case, living with roommates, driving a used car, cooking at home, etc.).

So you can spend money on the things that DO matter to you (experiences, travel, socializing with friends)‚Ä¶AND still have money to invest for your future.

Unless you have an extremely high income, you‚Äôre not going to be able to have the nicest apt, a brand new car, doordash dinner and eat out lunch, the fanciest clothes, travel all the time, and still save for retirement.

You simply can‚Äôt have everything, unless you want to work until you‚Äôre 70 years old. That‚Äôs why you need to prioritize your spending and if experiences/travel are important to you, then prioritize them, but you‚Äôre probably going to have to give something else up.

description:
READ BELOW FOR WHY I‚ÄôM HAPPY I INVESTED IN MY 20s ‚¨áÔ∏è üòÄ

When I was 23, I didn‚Äôt know why I was investing so much money (it was a lot for me). I just knew it was the right thing to do because of the power of compounding.

10 years later and I‚Äôm so happy that I invested what I did. It‚Äôs given our family a ton of financial security and flexibility.

I was too busy partying at 23 to even know what my life would like 10 years into the future. But now at 33, I can look back and at least share my journey and lessons with you all.

If you know you want a family in the future, you might as well start thinking a little bit about your financial future now.

It doesn‚Äôt have to be anything crazy, but if you‚Äôre wasting $500/month on junk, think about how much financial security and freedom that can provide your future family if you invest that $500 every month and you do that for 10 years.

It‚Äôs sometimes hard to picture that or imagine that far into the future. That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm so transparent about my finances on social media. So you can see what‚Äôs possible if you save/invest like I did. Even if you did half of what I did, you would still have a lot of money.

I‚Äôm not telling you to skip that trip with your friends or to eat at home every meal‚Ä¶I just want you to truly think about how you‚Äôre spending every dollar and make sure it aligns with you values and your future aspirations. Especially if you want a family.

Also, this video is 7 months old lol. I just never posted it from my drafts. But it‚Äôs cool that my net worth has grown from $540K to $600K in that timeframe. The power of investing.

Because I invested so much in my 20s and I now have $450K invested at 33. This money is going to stay invested for 25 more years and I‚Äôll have $3-$5 million when I‚Äôm in my late 50s.

Comment ‚ÄúPORTFOLIO‚Äù and I‚Äôll send you a link to see my entire portfolio of exactly which index funds I invest in.

description:
The question I get the most is, ‚ÄúI have x amount of money. What should I do with it?‚Äù

I always refer people to the 7 steps that I show in this video.

They are the fundamental building blocks of personal finance and how your dollars should be deployed for you.

They are taken directly from the @reddit personal finance subreddit flow chart and I would say they apply to 90% of people unless you‚Äôre trying to invest heavy into real estate or your own business or something similar.

But for most people working a w2 job, these steps are going to apply.

Learn these steps and understand them so you can apply them to your life.

I don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs any harder than something you would learn in middle school and it‚Äôs going to have a much bigger impact on your life than geometry.

One of the big steps is getting your 401K match. It‚Äôs like free money from your employer. Just make sure you understand the vesting terms. But a 401K match is the only time in your life where you will get a 100% or 50% return on your money. So it‚Äôs a very advantageous thing to do.

#401K #personalfinance

description:

Most people don‚Äôt realize that ‚Äúsemi-retired‚Äù is a thing. Usually you just work til you‚Äôre 65. And then you have a retirement party. And then you just completely stop working.

But truthfully, there are endless options to design a ‚Äúsemi-retirement‚Äù if you have the financial means.

Investing as much as you can as early as you can is the best way to give yourself the option to potentially ‚Äúsemi-retire‚Äù if that interests you.
